Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

The data comes from the FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Check System(NICS). The NICS is used to determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Gun shops call into this system to ensure that each custoer does not have a criminal record or isn't otherwise ineliginle to make a purchase. The data has been supplemented with state level data fromcensus.gov.

The first table is made up of 27 columns:

  1. 'month'
  2. 'state'
  3. 'permit'
  4. 'permit_recheck'
  5. 'handgun'
  6. 'long_gun'
  7. 'other'
  8. 'multiple'
  9. 'admin'
  10. 'prepawn_handgun'
  11. 'prepawn_long_gun'
  12. 'prepawn_other'
  13. 'redemption_handgun'
  14. 'redemption_long_gun'
  15. 'redemption_other'
  16. 'returned_handgun'
  17. 'returned_long_gun',
  18. 'returned_other'
  19. 'rentals_handgun'
  20. 'rentals_long_gun',
  21. 'private_sale_handgun'
  22. 'private_sale_long_gun'
  23. 'private_sale_other'
  24. 'return_to_seller_handgun'
  25. 'return_to_seller_long_gun'
  26. 'return_to_seller_other'
  27. 'totals'

Each column represents the type of transaction submitted to the NICS. Each type of transaction is broken down by the type of firearm.

  • Hand Gun - ) any firearm which has a short stock and is designed to be held and fired by the use of a single hand; and (b) any combination of parts from which a firearm described in paragraph (a) can be assembled
  • Long Gun - a weapon designed or redesigned, made or remade to use the energy of the explosive in (a) a fixed metallic catridge to fire a single e projectile through a rifled bore for each single pull of the trigger; or (b) a fixed shotgun shell to fire through a smooth bore either a number of ball shot or a single projectile for each single pull of the trigger.
  • Other - refers to frames, receivers, and other firearms that are neither handguns nor long guns (rifles or shotguns), such as firearms having a pistol grip that expel a shotgun shell, or National Firearms Act firearms, including silencers.

Columns 1 and 2 denote the month and location of the transaction

Columns 3 - 9 are for background checks initiated by a officially-licensed Federal Firearms License(FFL) or criminal justice/law enforcement agency prior to the issuance of a firearm-related permit or transfer. The indication of “multiple” denotes a background check where more than one type of firearm is associated to a single background check and “admin” denotes the administrative checks that are for other authorized uses of the NICS.

Other types of transactions are explained below:

  • Pre-Pawn—background checks requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees seeking to pledge or pawn a firearm as security for the payment or repayment of money, prior to actually pledging or pawning the firearm.
  • Redemption—background checks requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees attempting to regain possession of a firearm after pledging or pawning a firearm as security at a pawn shop.
  • Returned/Disposition—background checks requested by criminal justice/law enforcement agencies prior to returning a firearm in its possession to the respective transferee, to ensure the individual is not prohibited.
  • Rentals—background checks requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees attempting to possess a firearm when the firearm is loaned or rented for use off the premises of the business.
  • Private Sale—background checks requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees attempting to possess a firearm from a private party seller who is not an officially-licensed FFL.
  • Return to Seller-Private Sale—background checks requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees attempting to possess a firearm from a private party seller who is not an officially-licensed FFL.

It is important to note that the statistics within this chart represent the number of firearm background checks initiated through the NICS. They do not represent the number of firearms sold. Based on varying state laws and purchase scenarios, a one-to-one correlation cannot be made between a firearm background check and a firearm sale

A method used to estimate the gun sales was documented by in a NYT analysis of the same data and used here

In [17]:
df_gun.fillna(value=0, inplace = True)

Create a new column estimate_total_sale for the estimated total sales corresponding to each entry

To convert background checks into estimated sales, we relied on a method suggested in the Small Arms Survey by Jurgen Brauer, a professor at Georgia Regents University. Each long gun and handgun check was counted as 1.1 sales. Each multiple-gun check was counted as two sales. Permit checks and other types of checks were omitted. The multiplier is an estimate based on Mr. Brauer's interviews with gun shop owners.

In [18]:
df_gun['estimated_total_sale'] = df_gun.iloc[:,4]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,5]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,7]*2 + df_gun.iloc[:,9]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,10]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,12]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,13]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,15]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,16]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,18]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,19]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,20]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,21]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,23]*1.1 + df_gun.iloc[:,24]*1.1

total_month_sales = df_gun.groupby('month', as_index= False).sum()['estimated_total_sale']
In [37]:

From the Above graph, we see an upward trend in both the purchase of firearms and number of background checks.

Both plots have 18 peaks corresponding to the 18 years plotted. This implies a seasonal trend.

An interesting thing to note is that some states such as Alaska, Colorado and Louisiana have more sales than background checks which makes them part of the small minority

Research Question 3(Which state had the highest growth of gun registrations)¶

To find which state had the highest growth of gun registration, I subtracted the most dated year from the most recent. I used the years 2016 and 2002 because the years 1998-2001 lacked data on some states such as the virgin islands and 2017 was incomplete

In [42]:
ttl2016=df_gun.query('year=="2016"').groupby('state').totals.sum()
In [43]:
ttl2002=df_gun.query('year=="2002"').groupby('state').totals.sum()
In [44]:
height=ttl2016-ttl2002
In [45]:
plt.subplots(figsize=(20,20))
plt.bar(labels, height)
plt.xticks(rotation='vertical')
plt.ylabel('Growth of Gun Registrations', fontdict={'fontsize': 15})
plt.xlabel('States', fontdict={'fontsize': 15})
plt.title('Growth of Gun Registrations between 2002 and 2016', fontdict={'fontsize':20});

From the above chart, we can see that kentucky had the highest growth of gun registrations from 2002 to 2016

The virgin islands have one of the lowest growth gun registrations despite having nearly no gun registrations in 2002

Conclusions¶

Q1 - From the results of the first question, we see that there has been a steady growth in the ownership of guns in the USA. We can also infer that the NCIS has gotten better at carrying out these background checks as can be seen by the increasing difference between the gun sales and gun checks. Further research into this is adviced

Q2 - The state with the most background checks was kentucky; followed by Utah and California. The state with the most sales is Utah; followed by California and Puerto Rico. The common trend is for the background checks to be greater than gun sales although there are exceptions to this. Further research is advised into te cause fpr this

Q3 - Kentucky had the highest gun growth; followed by California and Illinois

Q4 - From the results, the census data most closely related to gun per capita is the median gross rent. It has a negative correlation with it and as such, the lower the rent, the more people in the community own guns. Other factors that influence gun ownership include race,population and curiously, travel time to work. Further researc is required.

Limitations¶

The biggest limitation is the lack of accurate sales data. Conclusions made from analysing the sales data are thus not completely accurate,
